    "summary": "The Frankish Kingdom under Clovis I (r. 481–511 AD) was the most consequential of the post-Roman Germanic states, laying the foundation for medieval France and the Carolingian Empire. Clovis united the various Frankish tribes, defeated the last Roman governor Syagrius in 486, repelled the Alemanni at the Battle of Tolbiac (c. 496), defeated the Visigoths at the [[event:2832|Battle of Vouillé]] (507) and pushed them out of Gaul, and by his death controlled most of modern France and Belgium. His conversion to Nicene (Catholic) Christianity — as opposed to the Arian Christianity of the other Germanic kingdoms — was perhaps his most historically significant act.\n\nClovis's baptism, reportedly in 496 or 508, was performed by Bishop Remigius of Reims. By converting to Catholicism rather than Arianism, Clovis gained the active support of the Gallo-Roman church, the most powerful institutional force in the former western provinces, and legitimacy among the Roman-descended population. This alliance between the Frankish monarchy and the Catholic Church became the defining feature of medieval European politics — it was the foundation on which Charlemagne would later build the Holy Roman Empire. The Merovingian dynasty Clovis founded ruled France until it was supplanted by the Carolingians in 751.",
